1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:07,809
You enter true agent territory when the execution path cannot be predicted and the model must keep adapting its plan from environmental results.

2
00:00:07,759 --> 00:00:10,519
The core of an agent is not mysterious.

3
00:00:10,519 --> 00:00:12,740
It is a continuing decision loop.

4
00:00:12,740 --> 00:00:19,442
The model interprets the goal, chooses an action, calls a tool, reads the real result, and updates its plan.

5
00:00:19,442 --> 00:00:24,932
The loop continues until the task completes, reaches a blocker, or hits a stopping condition.

6
00:00:24,932 --> 00:00:28,346
The critical question is not how long the model reasons.

7
00:00:28,346 --> 00:00:31,884
It is whether each action produces reliable ground truth.

8
00:00:31,884 --> 00:00:35,711
After a coding agent changes a file, it can run tests.

9
00:00:35,711 --> 00:00:40,211
After a support agent issues a refund, it can read the API response.

10
00:00:40,211 --> 00:00:45,403
After a browser agent clicks a button, it can verify that the page changed as expected.

11
00:00:45,403 --> 00:00:49,307
That feedback is how an agent knows whether it is making progress.

12
00:00:49,307 --> 00:00:56,942
Customer support and coding are strong agent tasks because they combine conversation with action and offer relatively clear success criteria.

13
00:00:56,942 --> 00:01:00,288
Autonomy also raises cost and compounds error.

14
00:01:00,288 --> 00:01:07,798
If every step were ninety percent reliable, ten correct steps in a row would have a theoretical probability of only about thirty-five percent.

15
00:01:07,798 --> 00:01:15,423
Real systems use checks and retries, but the arithmetic makes the boundary obvious: a longer path cannot rely on confidence alone.

16
00:01:15,423 --> 00:01:24,951
Production agents therefore need sandboxes, permission limits, maximum iterations, explicit stopping rules, and human confirmation at critical actions.

17
00:01:24,951 --> 00:01:31,894
They also need a record of tool calls and environment responses so a failure can be diagnosed, replayed, and recovered.

18
00:01:31,894 --> 00:01:34,586
An agent is not the absence of control.

19
00:01:34,586 --> 00:01:39,778
It gives dynamic decisions to the model and rebuilds control through feedback and boundaries.

20
00:01:39,778 --> 00:01:45,634
Reversible actions, such as reading information or drafting text, can receive wider autonomy.

21
00:01:45,634 --> 00:01:51,423
Payments, deletion, and external messages should receive narrow permissions and pre-action approval.

22
00:01:51,423 --> 00:02:00,509
A practical risk ladder is: automate low-risk actions, inspect medium-risk actions after execution, and approve high-risk actions before execution.

23
00:02:00,509 --> 00:02:02,048
Chapter recap.

24
00:02:02,048 --> 00:02:05,894
First, every action must read real environmental feedback.

25
00:02:05,894 --> 00:02:10,048
Second, failure risk compounds across a long execution path.

26
00:02:10,048 --> 00:02:13,974
Third, autonomy requires permissions and stopping conditions.
